        <h2><i class="fas fa-seedling"></i> Five Core Propagation Methods with Tasmanian Focus</h2>
        <div class="stat-grid"><div class="stat-card"><i class="fas fa-seedling"></i><h3>Seed</h3><p>Sexual · Genetic diversity · Orthodox/recalcitrant</p></div><div class="stat-card"><i class="fas fa-cut"></i><h3>Cuttings</h3><p>Asexual · True-to-type · Clone production</p></div><div class="stat-card"><i class="fas fa-hand-holding-heart"></i><h3>Division</h3><p>Clumping species · Grasses · Ferns</p></div><div class="stat-card"><i class="fas fa-graft"></i><h3>Grafting</h3><p>Cultivars · Difficult species</p></div><div class="stat-card"><i class="fas fa-seedling"></i><h3>Layering</h3><p>Simple propagation · Ground/mound</p></div></div>
        <div class="grid-2">

            <div class="card"><i class="fas fa-seedling"></i><div class="card-title">1. Seed Propagation</div><p><strong>Tasmanian natives:</strong> <em>Eucalyptus globulus, Acacia melanoxylon, Banksia marginata, Nothofagus cunninghamii, Melaleuca ericifolia, Allocasuarina verticillata</em></p><p><strong>Pre-treatments:</strong><br>• <strong>Hot water scarification:</strong> Acacia, Kennedia, Indigofera, Hardenbergia (pour boiling water, soak 12-24h)<br>• <strong>Cold stratification:</strong> Pomaderris, Eucalyptus coccifera, Richea, Astelia (2-5°C, 6-10 weeks in moist sand/vermiculite)<br>• <strong>Smoke water:</strong> Banksia, Stylidium, Anigozanthos, many heath species (Epacridaceae) – apply as pre-soak or mist<br>• <strong>Mechanical scarification:</strong> For hard-seeded species – nicking seed coat with file<br>• <strong>Sowing depth:</strong> 2-3× seed diameter; fine seeds surface sow with thin vermiculite cover<br><strong>Media:</strong> Sterile seed-raising mix, low phosphorus for natives (Proteaceae sensitive). pH 5.5-6.5 ideal.</p><p><strong>Seed longevity:</strong> Orthodox seeds (Eucalyptus, Acacia) can be stored at 5°C for 5-10 years. Recalcitrant seeds (Nothofagus, Atherosperma) must be sown within weeks.</p></div>

            <div class="card"><i class="fas fa-cut"></i><div class="card-title">2. Vegetative Cuttings</div><p><strong>Softwood cuttings</strong> (spring-early summer): <em>Leptospermum, Melaleuca, Correa, Callistemon, Westringia</em> – IBA 2000-3000ppm, high humidity (85-95%), bottom heat 22-25°C.<br><strong>Semi-hardwood</strong> (late summer-autumn): <em>Prostanthera, Westringia, Hakea, Grevillea</em> – IBA 3000-4000ppm, mist system, partial shade.<br><strong>Hardwood</strong> (winter): deciduous species, some eucalypts from juvenile stock, <em>Populus, Salix</em> (for riparian restoration) – IBA 1000-2000ppm, outdoor beds.<br><strong>Root cuttings:</strong> For species like <em>Banksia serrata, Acacia verticillata</em> – collect in winter, 5-10cm sections, horizontal placement.<br><strong>Rooting hormone (IBA):</strong> hastens root initiation, increases percentage, improves root quality and uniformity. Available in powder, gel, and liquid formulations.</p></div>

            <div class="card"><i class="fas fa-hand-holding-heart"></i><div class="card-title">3. Division & Layering</div><p><strong>Division:</strong> Ideal for clumping species: <em>Poa labillardierei, Lomandra longifolia, Gahnia grandis, Dianella tasmanica, Dicksonia antarctica, Stipa stipoides, Carex appressa</em>. Divide in early spring or autumn, ensure each division has 3-5 healthy shoots and fibrous roots. Use sharp spade or knife.<br><strong>Layering:</strong> Peg low branch into soil, cover, sever when rooted. Works for <em>Rhododendron, Prostanthera, Boronia, Correa</em>. Air layering for taller species – girdle branch, apply rooting hormone, wrap with moist sphagnum and plastic.</p><p><strong>Fern propagation:</strong> Spore collection for Dicksonia, Blechnum, Polystichum – requires sterile media and high humidity.</p></div>
            <div class="card"><i class="fas fa-graft"></i><div class="card-title">4. Grafting & Budding</div><p>Used for cultivars and difficult-to-root species. <strong>Whip & tongue</strong> for equal diameter scion/rootstock; <strong>cleft graft</strong> for larger rootstock; <strong>side-veneer graft</strong> for evergreen species.<br><strong>Key principles:</strong> Match cambium layers (essential for vascular connection), seal with grafting tape/wax, keep humid until callus forms (2-6 weeks).<br><strong>Tasmanian context:</strong> Grafting of <em>Eucalyptus</em> cultivars, <em>Telopea truncata</em> for improved flowering, <em>Prostanthera</em> for colour forms. Rootstocks: <em>Eucalyptus gunnii</em> for cold tolerance, <em>Eucalyptus globulus</em> for vigour.</p><p><strong>T-budding:</strong> Summer technique for <em>Rosa</em> (native roses) and selected fruit trees used in conservation plantings.</p></div>
        </div>

